The above pairplot shows that the different salary categories overlap a lot. Therefore, any linear classifier won't be able to produce good results. The same was the case in the experiment of perceptron and linear regression. The overlapping datapoints clearly state that we have to use a model that can deal with non-linear dataset easily.

Function to display the datapoints and the decision regions for the different salary categories. It also encircles the different points that are used as test points

In [7]:
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
def plot_decision_regions(X, y, classifier,test_idx=None, resolution=0.02):
    # setup marker generator and color map
    markers = ('s', 'x', 'o', '^', 'v')
    colors = ('red', 'blue', 'lightgreen', 'gray', 'cyan')
    cmap = ListedColormap(colors[:len(np.unique(y))])

    # plot the decision surface
    x1_min, x1_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
    x2_min, x2_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
    xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x1_min, x1_max, resolution),
                         np.arange(x2_min, x2_max, resolution))
    Z = classifier.predict(np.array([xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()]).T)
    Z = Z.reshape(xx1.shape)
    
    plt.contourf(xx1, xx2, Z, alpha=0.4, cmap=cmap)
    plt.xlim(xx1.min(), xx1.max())
    plt.ylim(xx2.min(), xx2.max())

    # plot class samples
    for idx, cl in enumerate(np.unique(y)):
        plt.scatter(x=X[np.where(y == cl), 0], y=X[np.where(y == cl), 1], alpha=0.8, c=cmap(idx), marker=markers[idx], label=cl)
    
    # highlight test samples
    if test_idx:
        X_test, y_test = X[test_idx, :], y[test_idx]
        plt.scatter(X_test[:, 0], X_test[:, 1], c='',edgecolor='black',alpha=1.0, linewidths=1, marker='o',s=55, label='test set')

The function below, standardizes the datapoints, splits the dataset into 7:3 ratio for training set and test set. Trains the Logistic Regression model on the training set and predicts the accuracy score using the test set. Then it plots the decision region for the model along with the datapoints in both the training set and test set

In [30]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

def standarize_and_plot_Logistic(X, y, xlab, ylab):
    X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.3, random_state=0) 
    
    sc = StandardScaler()
    sc.fit(X_train)
    X_train_std = sc.transform(X_train)
    X_test_std = sc.transform(X_test)
    X_combined_std = np.vstack((X_train_std, X_test_std))
    y_combined = np.hstack((y_train, y_test))
    
    lr = LogisticRegression(C=1000.0, random_state=0)
    lr.fit(X_train_std, y_train)
    
    y_pred = lr.predict(X_test_std)

#     print(lr.predict_proba(X_test_std[0,:]))
    
    plot_decision_regions(X_combined_std, y_combined, classifier=lr, test_idx=range(105,200,5))
    plt.xlabel(xlab + ' [standardized]')
    plt.ylabel(ylab + ' [standardized]')
    plt.legend(loc='upper left')
    plt.show()
    
    print('Accuracy: %.2f%%' % (accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)*100))

Applying Logistic Regression to 'Domain' and 'Agreeableness'

Accuracy: 36.75%

Plotting the 'ComputerProgramming' & 'Quant' features accroding to their categories and on using Logistic Regression for seperating them, a significant increase in accuracy score (36.75%) is observed. This is the best result that we have achieved compared to other pairs of attributes. But still, only a 36% accuracy is not good for future prediction when used in real time. So we have to come up with different learning model which gives a higher accuracy atleast of 50% and for that we need a complex model that can work on higher dimension in space so that there is lesser overlapping of datapoints. We will see that in later experiments.
